<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900921-0052</DOCNO><DOCID>900921-0052.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Two German Parliaments   Ratify Unification Treaty</HL><DATE>09/21/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10</SO><CO>   EUROP TAXES</CO><LP>   FRANKFURT, West Germany -- The two German parliamentsindependently ratified the treaty that will officially unifytheir nations Oct. 3.   But the long day of debate in the West German Bundestagwas marked by fierce skirmishes over the costs ofunification, particularly on whether new taxes are needed.The question of whether German troops should be allowed todeploy outside the boundaries of the North Atlantic TreatyOrganization also generated heated words, as politicianslooked beyond Oct. 3 and began to stake out campaign standsfor the first all-German elections, on Dec. 2.</LP><TEXT>   The 1,000-page unification treaty details how allfunctions of the East German state will be united with thoseof West Germany under one government and parliament. For EastGermany's parliament, the Volkskammer, the vote was its lastimportant business before its dissolution in two weeks.   The Bundestag approved the treaty by 442-47; theVolkskammer, by 299-80.</TEXT></DOC>